But let's begin with a very,

67
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:31,060
very lightening review

68
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:34,520
of the last quarter of quantum mechanics.

69
00:02:35,180 --> 00:02:36,140
First of all,

70
00:02:36,140 --> 00:02:38,350
the whole story begins by asking how

71
00:02:38,350 --> 00:02:40,560
do you represent the state of a system.

72
00:02:40,820 --> 00:02:42,460
We could go back a step

73
00:02:42,460 --> 00:02:44,100
and ask what is a system,

74
00:02:44,220 --> 00:02:45,820
but I'll assume you know what a system is.

75
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:48,560
And how do you represent the states of a system.

76
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:50,960
In classical mechanics,

77
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:53,780
the states of a system are represented as points

78
00:02:53,780 --> 00:02:55,120
in phase space.

79
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:56,820
In quantum mechanics,

80
00:02:56,820 --> 00:02:59,100
they're represented by state vectors.

81
00:02:59,740 --> 00:03:02,040
The idea of a vector is not

82
00:03:02,040 --> 00:03:04,340
a vector like a pointer in space,

83
00:03:04,440 --> 00:03:06,140
pointing in a certain direction in space.

84
00:03:06,420 --> 00:03:07,780
It's an abstract notion.

85
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:09,820
You can add vectors.

86
00:03:10,300 --> 00:03:12,440
You can multiply them by constants.

87
00:03:12,760 --> 00:03:16,370
And the mathematical structure of a state vector

88
00:03:16,370 --> 00:03:19,980
is a mathematical vector in a vector space.

89
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:22,640
The vector space is not three-dimensional,

90
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:24,120
except in special cases.

91
00:03:24,420 --> 00:03:25,920
It could be any-dimensional.

92
00:03:26,400 --> 00:03:28,080
So we represent states

93
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:33,780
by state vectors,

94
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:36,060
and the symbol for a state vector

95
00:03:37,880 --> 00:03:40,640
is Dirac's ket symbol,

96
00:03:40,940 --> 00:03:41,420
ket,

97
00:03:41,420 --> 00:03:42,240
K-E-T,

98
00:03:42,520 --> 00:03:46,080
which is the latter half of the term braket,

99
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:49,340
like bra-ket or bra-ket.

100
00:03:49,580 --> 00:03:52,620
Every state can be either represented by a ket symbol

101
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:56,720
or by a corresponding bra-vector.

102
00:03:58,460 --> 00:03:59,060
Together,

103
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:01,420
we often put them together to form a braket,

104
00:04:01,620 --> 00:04:02,360
or a bracket.

105
00:04:05,640 --> 00:04:08,260
The bra-vectors are in one-to-one

106
00:04:08,260 --> 00:04:10,880
correspondence with the ket vectors,

107
00:04:11,060 --> 00:04:13,130
and you should really think of

108
00:04:13,130 --> 00:04:15,200
them roughly as being the complex conjugates,

109
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:19,220
in the same sense as complex conjugates of complex numbers.

110
00:04:20,019 --> 00:04:22,620
Complex numbers are ubiquitous.

111
00:04:22,640 --> 00:04:23,420
They are part of the mechanism of the quantum mechanics,

112
00:04:23,940 --> 00:04:25,600
and so are complex vectors.

113
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:28,360
So state vectors are represented by,

114
00:04:28,420 --> 00:04:29,180
or states,

115
00:04:29,420 --> 00:04:31,440
states are represented by state vectors.

116
00:04:32,060 --> 00:04:33,320
The state vectors,

117
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:34,240
well,

118
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:35,280
we could say a little bit more,

119
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:37,780
but if I were to say the whole thing,

120
00:04:37,780 --> 00:04:38,160
of course,

121
00:04:38,220 --> 00:04:39,880
we would then go through the entire quarter,

122
00:04:40,460 --> 00:04:41,080
so I won't.

123
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:42,180
In addition,

124
00:04:42,180 --> 00:04:43,740
there are observables,

125
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:44,740
things that you measure.

126
00:04:45,940 --> 00:04:47,420
Measurables are observables.

127
00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:52,580
In classical mechanics,

128
00:04:52,580 --> 00:04:54,080
there are also observables.

129
00:04:54,140 --> 00:04:55,280
They're the things you measure,

130
00:04:55,340 --> 00:04:57,340
but we don't spend a lot

131
00:04:57,340 --> 00:04:59,340
of time talking about their mathematical structure.

132
00:04:59,780 --> 00:05:02,100
We just assume you know what I'm talking about

133
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:04,940
when I say position of a particle is measurable,

134
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:06,680
or momentum of a particle,

135
00:05:06,860 --> 00:05:08,080
or the energy of a particle,

136
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:09,080
or whatever.

137
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:10,360
In quantum mechanics,

138
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:12,050
we have to be very precise

139
00:05:12,050 --> 00:05:13,740
what we mean by an observable.

140
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:18,340
And observables are represented by

141
00:05:19,220 --> 00:05:19,740
linear,

142
00:05:19,740 --> 00:05:21,500
Hermitian operators.

143
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:24,640
I'll label them with,

144
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:25,400
what are these?

145
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:26,040
Let's see.

146
00:05:26,460 --> 00:05:28,020
These are Greek letters.

147
00:05:28,140 --> 00:05:29,540
What kind of letters are those?

148
00:05:29,880 --> 00:05:30,220
English?

149
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:31,960
Roman?

150
00:05:31,960 --> 00:05:32,540
Latin?

151
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:33,340
I don't know.

152
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:35,220
Are they Latin?

153
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:35,940
Hmm?

154
00:05:36,180 --> 00:05:37,240
It's capital alpha.

155
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:38,400
Yeah,

156
00:05:38,400 --> 00:05:39,460
it's true.

157
00:05:39,460 --> 00:05:40,260
It's capital alpha.

158
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:42,120
Okay.

159
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:46,320
But Latin letters are representing observables,

160
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:47,780
and they are

161
00:05:47,780 --> 00:05:51,520
Hermitian operators that act on the vectors.

162
00:05:51,640 --> 00:05:52,140
Hermitian,

163
00:05:52,140 --> 00:05:53,100
for our purposes,

164
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:59,220
translates or is the quantum mechanical equivalent of real.

165
00:05:59,420 --> 00:06:02,860
Real as in real or complex or imaginary.

166
00:06:05,120 --> 00:06:07,440
They are the real operators

167
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:11,640
which are equal to their own Hermitian conjugate.

168
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:16,400
Every such operator

169
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:19,400
in the space of states is called an observable,

170
00:06:19,540 --> 00:06:23,100
and presumably there is really a way to observe it.

171
00:06:26,159 --> 00:06:28,800
The eigenvalues and eigenvectors

172
00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:32,220
of these Hermitian operators play a special role.

173
00:06:32,420 --> 00:06:33,460
So let me just remind you,

174
00:06:33,500 --> 00:06:36,300
what is an eigenvalue and an eigenvector?

175
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:38,800
If you have a Hermitian operator,

176
00:06:40,190 --> 00:06:43,060
you can search for vectors.

177
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:47,120
Let's label the vector.

178
00:06:50,320 --> 00:06:52,100
Let's label it little a.

179
00:06:54,060 --> 00:06:55,520
Or better yet,

180
00:06:55,520 --> 00:06:55,980
alpha,

181
00:06:56,100 --> 00:06:58,020
since we want to label it with a Greek index.

182
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:01,240
Let's label it with an alpha.

183
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:04,280
And a,

184
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:05,400
being an operator,

185
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:07,020
can act on alpha,

186
00:07:07,220 --> 00:07:10,500
and alpha is an eigenvector of a

187
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:13,040
if the action is a.

188
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:15,580
So the action of a is just to multiply

189
00:07:16,260 --> 00:07:18,480
the vector alpha by a number.

190
00:07:18,680 --> 00:07:19,940
In this case,

191
00:07:19,940 --> 00:07:21,660
I'm using a redundant notation,

192
00:07:21,980 --> 00:07:25,760
the same notation for the eigenvalue and the eigenvector.

193
00:07:26,300 --> 00:07:28,400
And this says that the eigenvalue,

194
00:07:28,520 --> 00:07:29,820
the eigenvector alpha,

195
00:07:30,040 --> 00:07:33,700
is an eigenvector of a with eigenvalue alpha.

196
00:07:34,300 --> 00:07:36,420
And the significance of that equation

197
00:07:36,420 --> 00:07:37,980
is that,

198
00:07:37,980 --> 00:07:39,080
first of all,

199
00:07:39,100 --> 00:07:41,420
the set of eigenvalues

200
00:07:41,420 --> 00:07:43,280
of an operator,

201
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:44,620
or of an observable,

202
00:07:44,640 --> 00:07:48,300
are the set of possible results of measurement.

203
00:07:49,580 --> 00:07:51,260
If you have a quantity,

204
00:07:51,380 --> 00:07:52,940
which when you measure it,

205
00:07:52,980 --> 00:07:54,980
can take on the value 1,

206
00:07:54,980 --> 00:07:55,420
3,

207
00:07:55,420 --> 00:07:56,040
and 7,

208
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:58,860
then the eigenvalues of that operator

209
00:07:58,860 --> 00:07:59,520
are 1,

210
00:07:59,520 --> 00:07:59,940
3,

211
00:07:59,940 --> 00:08:00,540
and 7,

212
00:08:00,540 --> 00:08:01,600
and so forth.

213
00:08:02,460 --> 00:08:06,280
The eigenvectors are the state vectors of the system

214
00:08:07,060 --> 00:08:08,160
for which,

215
00:08:08,160 --> 00:08:10,140
if you make a measurement,

216
00:08:10,140 --> 00:08:12,120
the answer is definite,

217
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:13,960
not statistical,

218
00:08:15,980 --> 00:08:16,620
determined,

219
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:17,260
deterministic,

220
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:20,260
and the answer to the measurement is alpha.

221
00:08:20,520 --> 00:08:22,500
So I assume you all remember this.

222
00:08:22,580 --> 00:08:24,640
I'm doing this mostly to just refresh your memory.

223
00:08:27,640 --> 00:08:28,280
Now,

224
00:08:28,280 --> 00:08:30,380
the particular systems

225
00:08:30,380 --> 00:08:33,299
we're going to be discussing mostly in this quarter

226
00:08:33,299 --> 00:08:35,159
are systems of particles.

227
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:38,320
Particles are largely characterized

228
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:40,120
by saying that things which are not things

229
00:08:40,140 --> 00:08:41,640
which have a location in space,

230
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,960
an ordinary location in space.

231
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:45,240
For example,

232
00:08:45,240 --> 00:08:46,500
if space is one-dimensional,

233
00:08:46,840 --> 00:08:49,020
then a particle is a thing

234
00:08:49,020 --> 00:08:51,280
which has a coordinate x.

235
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:54,160
It's located somewhere as an x.

236
00:08:54,300 --> 00:08:55,720
If space is three-dimensional,

237
00:08:55,980 --> 00:08:57,160
then particles move around.

238
00:08:57,420 --> 00:08:58,000
They have x,

239
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:58,280
y,

240
00:08:58,280 --> 00:08:58,640
and z,

241
00:08:58,640 --> 00:08:59,400
and so forth.

242
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:02,780
Let's write formulas for the case of one dimension,

243
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:03,940
but I'll tell you what to do

244
00:09:03,940 --> 00:09:05,880
for three dimensions in a moment.

245
00:09:06,620 --> 00:09:07,140
Okay.

246
00:09:08,060 --> 00:09:08,580
Oh,

247
00:09:08,580 --> 00:09:09,100
sorry.

248
00:09:09,100 --> 00:09:10,820
Let's come back to one point

249
00:09:10,820 --> 00:09:12,940
that I need to emphasize.

250
00:09:13,420 --> 00:09:15,920
For every bra and every ket,

251
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:19,500
let's call the bra,

252
00:09:20,260 --> 00:09:21,500
let's call it phi.

253
00:09:21,880 --> 00:09:24,680
It is not necessarily the particular bra

254
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:25,980
that goes together with psi,

255
00:09:26,200 --> 00:09:27,500
with the ket psi.

256
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:29,740
For every pair like that,

257
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:31,120
there is an inner product.

258
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:32,800
There is a number.

259
00:09:32,960 --> 00:09:36,380
That number is in general a complex number,

260
00:09:37,199 --> 00:09:39,080
and it is represented as a number.

261
00:09:39,100 --> 00:09:40,100
It is represented as the inner product.

262
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:41,980
Inner product.

263
00:09:50,220 --> 00:09:51,560
And it's a number.

264
00:09:51,760 --> 00:09:54,080
It's a number for every pair of vectors.

265
00:09:55,340 --> 00:09:59,720
It represents a kind of product of the two vectors.

266
00:10:00,839 --> 00:10:03,320
It's similar in its mathematical structure

267
00:10:03,320 --> 00:10:05,620
to the dot product between two vectors

268
00:10:05,620 --> 00:10:06,520
in ordinary space,

269
00:10:07,520 --> 00:10:09,860
but it's a more abstract object.

270
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:12,400
It's the inner product between two vectors,

271
00:10:12,600 --> 00:10:14,720
and it plays an important role

272
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:16,520
in the logic of quantum mechanics.

273
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:18,000
In particular,

274
00:10:19,540 --> 00:10:20,840
if two states

275
00:10:21,620 --> 00:10:23,560
are distinguishable uniquely

276
00:10:24,420 --> 00:10:27,180
by the property that there's some observable

277
00:10:27,180 --> 00:10:28,440
that you could measure

278
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:30,800
which would be different than the two of them,

279
00:10:31,160 --> 00:10:33,460
let's suppose there's some quantity

280
00:10:33,460 --> 00:10:34,440
that you could measure,

281
00:10:34,440 --> 00:10:39,300
and it is definite

282
00:10:40,060 --> 00:10:43,940
that the answer in the state psi

283
00:10:43,940 --> 00:10:46,060
is different than the state phi,

284
00:10:46,340 --> 00:10:48,900
then we would say those two states

285
00:10:48,900 --> 00:10:49,940
are distinctly different.

286
00:10:50,080 --> 00:10:52,240
There's no chance of confusing them.

287
00:10:53,160 --> 00:10:54,520
There's a measurement you could do

288
00:10:54,520 --> 00:10:55,500
to distinguish them.

289
00:10:55,660 --> 00:10:58,280
Then those states are said to be orthogonal.

290
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:02,900
Orthogonal means physically identifiably different,

291
00:11:02,900 --> 00:11:05,340
and mathematically,

292
00:11:06,260 --> 00:11:09,100
it's the statement that the two vectors

293
00:11:09,100 --> 00:11:11,900
have inner product equal to zero.

294
00:11:13,940 --> 00:11:14,620
So,

295
00:11:14,620 --> 00:11:16,980
orthogonality is a fundamental property

296
00:11:16,980 --> 00:11:20,280
of relationships between vectors

297
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:22,140
which says that they are different.

298
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:23,720
You can't confuse them.

299
00:11:24,200 --> 00:11:24,780
Well,

300
00:11:24,780 --> 00:11:25,760
you can confuse them,

301
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:26,920
but you shouldn't confuse them.

302
00:11:29,060 --> 00:11:29,740
Okay.

303
00:11:30,780 --> 00:11:31,460
Now,

304
00:11:31,460 --> 00:11:32,600
when it comes to particles,

305
00:11:32,600 --> 00:11:34,540
the most important observable

306
00:11:34,540 --> 00:11:37,140
is the position of a particle.

307
00:11:37,460 --> 00:11:39,640
And so let's just discuss particles

308
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:40,740
moving on a line.

309
00:11:42,420 --> 00:11:44,460
The line is the x-axis.

310
00:11:46,220 --> 00:11:48,260
The location of the particle

311
00:11:48,260 --> 00:11:50,140
is just a value of x,

312
00:11:50,460 --> 00:11:51,860
and obviously,

313
00:11:51,860 --> 00:11:54,160
x should be thought of

314
00:11:54,160 --> 00:11:55,520
as an observable.

315
00:11:56,240 --> 00:11:57,000
Okay.

316
00:11:57,320 --> 00:11:58,540
In particular,

317
00:11:58,540 --> 00:12:00,120
there are states

318
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:06,520
which are labeled by a value of position.

319
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:08,560
Let's call it x-naught.

320
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:12,360
This is the point x-naught over here.

321
00:12:12,720 --> 00:12:14,240
I'm just using the naught here

322
00:12:14,240 --> 00:12:16,180
to indicate a particular position.

323
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:18,500
There are states

324
00:12:21,320 --> 00:12:23,500
which are labeled by x-naught,

325
00:12:23,580 --> 00:12:24,560
which have the property

326
00:12:25,220 --> 00:12:27,800
that if you measure the particle,

327
00:12:27,980 --> 00:12:29,120
the particle's position,

328
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:31,820
you will definitely find it at x-naught.

329
00:12:32,520 --> 00:12:33,120
Okay?

330
00:12:34,120 --> 00:12:34,720
Good.

331
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:37,540
The next concept...

332
00:12:38,199 --> 00:12:38,800
Oh,

333
00:12:38,800 --> 00:12:39,600
and of course,

334
00:12:41,020 --> 00:12:43,480
state vectors for different values,

335
00:12:43,700 --> 00:12:45,740
let's call them x and x-prime.

336
00:12:46,580 --> 00:12:49,900
If x and x-prime are two different positions,

337
00:12:50,100 --> 00:12:52,940
x and x-prime,

338
00:12:54,720 --> 00:12:56,700
then clearly those two states

339
00:12:56,700 --> 00:12:58,460
are distinguishable,

340
00:12:59,120 --> 00:13:01,140
operationally and by measurement,

341
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:02,300
they're distinguishable,

342
00:13:02,460 --> 00:13:04,700
so these two states are orthogonal.

343
00:13:06,079 --> 00:13:06,920
Now,

344
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:08,780
take any state,

345
00:13:08,980 --> 00:13:11,740
any state whatever of this particle,

346
00:13:11,900 --> 00:13:12,540
call it psi.

347
00:13:15,080 --> 00:13:16,860
Its inner product

348
00:13:18,920 --> 00:13:22,940
with the state representing the particle at x

349
00:13:22,940 --> 00:13:25,500
is called the wave function.

350
00:13:27,120 --> 00:13:29,100
The wave function of the particle,

351
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:30,840
and it's written as psi of x.

352
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:33,920
It's the psi that goes into the Schrodinger equation.

353
00:13:34,600 --> 00:13:35,820
It's Schrodinger's psi.

354
00:13:35,960 --> 00:13:37,680
I believe that Schrodinger was the first one

355
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:39,300
to call it psi.

356
00:13:40,840 --> 00:13:41,820
P-S-I.

357
00:13:47,580 --> 00:13:50,940
And the meaning of the wave function

358
00:13:51,500 --> 00:13:53,360
is closely related to,

359
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:54,640
but not the same,

360
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:56,240
as the probability

361
00:13:56,240 --> 00:13:59,680
that the particle is at position x.

362
00:14:01,180 --> 00:14:04,160
Psi of x is an arbitrary function.

363
00:14:04,420 --> 00:14:04,600
Well,

364
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:05,840
it's not completely arbitrary,

365
00:14:06,180 --> 00:14:08,400
but let's say it's some function.

366
00:14:09,780 --> 00:14:11,200
What does it represent?

367
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:12,140
Psi of x?

368
00:14:12,160 --> 00:14:14,900
Psi of x is closely related to the probability

369
00:14:14,900 --> 00:14:17,060
to find the particle at position x,

370
00:14:17,280 --> 00:14:18,880
but it's not quite that.

371
00:14:19,060 --> 00:14:20,620
The probability itself,

372
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:22,740
let's call it p of x,

373
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:33,240
is the product of the wave function

374
00:14:33,240 --> 00:14:34,880
times its complex conjugate.

375
00:14:35,500 --> 00:14:38,220
The wave function times its complex conjugate

376
00:14:38,220 --> 00:14:39,040
is positive.

377
00:14:39,620 --> 00:14:40,660
Any number,

378
00:14:40,660 --> 00:14:41,940
any complex number,

379
00:14:42,080 --> 00:14:43,500
times its own conjugate

380
00:14:43,500 --> 00:14:45,060
is always positive.

381
00:14:45,860 --> 00:14:47,580
Probabilities are always positive.

382
00:14:48,540 --> 00:14:51,540
Psi of x's are generally complex numbers.

383
00:14:52,180 --> 00:14:53,440
They can be positive,

384
00:14:53,440 --> 00:14:54,160
they can be negative,

385
00:14:54,280 --> 00:14:55,040
they can be imaginary,

386
00:14:55,040 --> 00:14:57,020
they can be whatever you like.

387
00:14:58,060 --> 00:15:00,400
So it would not make sense to say

388
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:02,180
that psi is a probability,

389
00:15:02,560 --> 00:15:04,060
but it does make sense to say

390
00:15:04,060 --> 00:15:06,380
psi times psi star is a probability.

391
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:07,960
Good,

392
00:15:07,960 --> 00:15:08,240
all right.

393
00:15:08,300 --> 00:15:12,380
That's the most important property of a particle,

394
00:15:12,540 --> 00:15:13,400
that it has a position.

395
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:16,220
It has eigenvectors

396
00:15:16,220 --> 00:15:20,680
which represent particles of known position.

397
00:15:22,480 --> 00:15:24,360
And we can construct,

398
00:15:24,360 --> 00:15:24,860
of course,

399
00:15:24,860 --> 00:15:25,920
a position operator.

400
00:15:26,620 --> 00:15:29,980
A position operator just multiplies

401
00:15:29,980 --> 00:15:32,140
psi of x by x itself.

402
00:15:32,820 --> 00:15:33,900
By x.

403
00:15:34,120 --> 00:15:36,160
So that's the idea of position.

404
00:15:36,700 --> 00:15:39,720
The other important observable for a particle,

405
00:15:39,940 --> 00:15:42,520
of course there are many observables for a particle,

406
00:15:43,040 --> 00:15:46,940
but the other particularly important one

407
00:15:46,940 --> 00:15:48,560
is called the what?

408
00:15:50,160 --> 00:15:51,160
The momentum.

409
00:15:51,880 --> 00:15:52,860
The momentum.

410
00:15:52,860 --> 00:15:55,920
In classical mechanics and in quantum mechanics,

411
00:15:56,220 --> 00:15:58,780
positions and momentum come together.

412
00:15:58,940 --> 00:15:59,060
Oh,

413
00:15:59,060 --> 00:15:59,940
before we do that,

414
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:05,620
I should discuss the issue of a particle moving

415
00:16:05,620 --> 00:16:06,980
not just in one dimension.

416
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:10,300
What happens if a particle is moving in three dimensions?

417
00:16:10,820 --> 00:16:11,720
In other words,

418
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:12,480
like a real particle.

419
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:16,100
Then it has three observable positions,

420
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:18,120
the three components of its position,

421
00:16:18,240 --> 00:16:18,780
namely x,

422
00:16:18,780 --> 00:16:19,000
y,

423
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:19,340
and z,

424
00:16:19,340 --> 00:16:19,900
if you like.

425
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:22,040
But since you can rotate axes,

426
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:26,660
you can just think of the position

427
00:16:27,220 --> 00:16:29,440
as a point in three-dimensional space.

428
00:16:29,860 --> 00:16:30,920
In that case,

429
00:16:30,920 --> 00:16:32,160
we would just think of x here

430
00:16:32,160 --> 00:16:33,880
as a point in three-dimensional space.

431
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:35,660
We could fill it out.

432
00:16:35,760 --> 00:16:37,580
We could fill out the equations by saying

433
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:43,000
there are states which represent particles

434
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,920
at known locations in three dimensions,

435
00:16:46,140 --> 00:16:46,320
x,

436
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:46,600
y,

437
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:46,980
and z.

438
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:50,020
This represents a particle located

439
00:16:50,660 --> 00:16:52,020
at a point in three dimensions.

440
00:16:52,020 --> 00:16:52,020
So,

441
00:16:52,020 --> 00:16:53,040
we would have a point in three-dimensional space

442
00:16:53,040 --> 00:16:54,180
over here,

443
00:16:54,180 --> 00:16:55,400
x,

444
00:16:55,400 --> 00:16:55,660
y,

445
00:16:55,660 --> 00:16:55,960
and z.

446
00:16:56,580 --> 00:16:58,700
And the rules would be similar,

447
00:16:58,700 --> 00:16:59,620
very similar.

448
00:17:00,340 --> 00:17:04,020
The inner products of x prime,

449
00:17:04,020 --> 00:17:04,900
y prime,

450
00:17:04,900 --> 00:17:05,599
z prime,

451
00:17:07,579 --> 00:17:13,240
that would be zero if there's any mismatch,

452
00:17:14,140 --> 00:17:16,599
not if x is not equal to x prime

453
00:17:16,599 --> 00:17:17,819
and y is not equal to y,

454
00:17:17,900 --> 00:17:19,819
but if the entire point,

455
00:17:22,020 --> 00:17:22,579
if the entire point is not the same

456
00:17:22,579 --> 00:17:23,940
as the point x prime,

457
00:17:23,940 --> 00:17:24,400
y prime,

458
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:24,859
z prime,

459
00:17:25,480 --> 00:17:30,360
then these are observably different positions

460
00:17:30,360 --> 00:17:31,140
for a particle,

461
00:17:31,300 --> 00:17:34,000
and the states are orthogonal to each other.

462
00:17:35,380 --> 00:17:37,900
I'm going to suppress the y and z,

463
00:17:38,540 --> 00:17:43,660
but keep in mind that the position of a particle

464
00:17:43,660 --> 00:17:46,380
depends on the dimensionality of the space

465
00:17:46,380 --> 00:17:47,320
that we're talking about,

466
00:17:47,540 --> 00:17:49,120
and in the real world,

467
00:17:49,120 --> 00:17:50,240
space is three-dimensional.

468
00:17:52,020 --> 00:17:52,300
Okay,

469
00:17:52,300 --> 00:17:54,040
for each component of position,

470
00:17:54,300 --> 00:17:56,320
there is also a component of momentum.

471
00:17:57,120 --> 00:17:58,760
In classical physics,

472
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:01,120
for non-relativistic classical physics,

473
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:03,240
the momentum is just the mass

474
00:18:03,240 --> 00:18:05,260
times that component of the velocity.

475
00:18:06,180 --> 00:18:07,580
In quantum mechanics,

476
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:10,620
the momentum is also an observable,

477
00:18:10,760 --> 00:18:13,740
and is also represented by an operator,

478
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:15,100
by a Hermitian operator.

479
00:18:17,220 --> 00:18:19,360
Hermitian operators can be thought of

480
00:18:19,360 --> 00:18:22,000
in the abstract as objects of the same nature,

481
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:25,660
objects which act on mathematical vectors,

482
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:27,360
the space of states,

483
00:18:27,820 --> 00:18:30,560
or they can be thought of more concretely

484
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:34,000
as operations on wave functions.

485
00:18:34,640 --> 00:18:35,880
Either one.

486
00:18:36,040 --> 00:18:37,740
You can think of them concretely

487
00:18:37,740 --> 00:18:41,240
as operations that you...

488
00:18:41,240 --> 00:18:43,120
What about x itself?

489
00:18:43,620 --> 00:18:45,580
What is the operation

490
00:18:46,659 --> 00:18:50,220
that represents the operator x?

491
00:18:50,780 --> 00:18:51,300
Well,

492
00:18:51,300 --> 00:18:53,360
it's just taking the state vector,

493
00:18:53,500 --> 00:18:54,400
the psi of x,

494
00:18:54,480 --> 00:18:55,400
or taking the wave function,

495
00:18:56,040 --> 00:18:58,960
and multiplying it by x.

496
00:18:59,560 --> 00:19:02,920
If psi of x is a function

497
00:19:05,860 --> 00:19:08,400
representing the probability amplitude,

498
00:19:08,920 --> 00:19:10,820
psi of x is called the probability amplitude

499
00:19:10,820 --> 00:19:12,120
or the wave function of a particle,

500
00:19:12,320 --> 00:19:15,040
then if you want to apply

501
00:19:15,040 --> 00:19:17,780
the operator representing position

502
00:19:17,780 --> 00:19:19,120
to psi of x,

503
00:19:19,120 --> 00:19:21,000
you just multiply psi of x by x.

504
00:19:21,340 --> 00:19:21,940
That's all.

505
00:19:24,120 --> 00:19:25,980
The eigenvectors of x

506
00:19:25,980 --> 00:19:27,620
are the wave functions

507
00:19:27,620 --> 00:19:29,140
which are highly peaked,

508
00:19:29,360 --> 00:19:29,760
very,

509
00:19:29,760 --> 00:19:30,460
very narrow,

510
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:32,780
Dirac delta functions.

511
00:19:33,460 --> 00:19:34,100
All right,

512
00:19:34,100 --> 00:19:34,740
in the same way,

513
00:19:34,860 --> 00:19:37,780
the momentum operator...

514
00:19:37,780 --> 00:19:37,960
Now,

515
00:19:37,960 --> 00:19:40,580
I'm not going to explain this in detail.

516
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:41,280
For this,

517
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:42,680
you go back to the lecture notes,

518
00:19:42,800 --> 00:19:45,500
or to the lectures themselves.

519
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:49,100
What lecture was it that we talked about

520
00:19:49,120 --> 00:19:49,800
about momentum?

521
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:50,680
Anybody remember?

522
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:51,320
Art?

523
00:19:53,060 --> 00:19:54,060
Several of them,

524
00:19:54,060 --> 00:19:56,160
but I think around eight.

525
00:19:56,860 --> 00:19:57,680
Around eight?

526
00:19:58,460 --> 00:19:59,020
Yeah,

527
00:19:59,020 --> 00:19:59,260
yeah,

528
00:19:59,260 --> 00:19:59,380
yeah,

529
00:19:59,380 --> 00:19:59,620
eight.

530
00:19:59,700 --> 00:20:00,620
Eight was...

531
00:20:01,720 --> 00:20:02,420
That's right.

532
00:20:02,580 --> 00:20:04,500
I remember with great grief

533
00:20:05,300 --> 00:20:06,260
lecture eight,

534
00:20:06,260 --> 00:20:06,560
right?

535
00:20:07,280 --> 00:20:07,840
Okay.

536
00:20:08,540 --> 00:20:10,960
So the momentum of a particle

537
00:20:11,860 --> 00:20:14,320
is represented by an operator called p,

538
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:23,120
and p also does something to psi of x.

539
00:20:24,760 --> 00:20:26,310
What it does to psi

540
00:20:26,310 --> 00:20:27,860
of x is it differentiates it.

541
00:20:28,680 --> 00:20:31,000
It differentiates it with respect to x,

542
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:32,100
but not quite.

543
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:35,600
The real thing is that

544
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:38,100
it multiplies it by minus i,

545
00:20:39,500 --> 00:20:41,100
the complex number i.

546
00:20:41,620 --> 00:20:44,060
There's a factor of Planck's constant,

547
00:20:44,180 --> 00:20:44,300
and that's the constant of the momentum.

548
00:20:44,300 --> 00:20:44,420
So it's a constant,

549
00:20:44,420 --> 00:20:45,760
h bar,

550
00:20:46,040 --> 00:20:48,260
and then it differentiates psi,

551
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:49,300
d by dx,

552
00:20:51,020 --> 00:20:52,120
psi of x.

553
00:20:55,820 --> 00:20:57,740
That is the operator

554
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:00,660
that acts on wave functions

555
00:21:00,660 --> 00:21:06,580
that represents the observable momentum.

556
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:10,580
Everybody remember this?

557
00:21:11,320 --> 00:21:12,000
Yeah.

558
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:13,900
We went through it.

559
00:21:14,340 --> 00:21:15,220
Okay,

560
00:21:15,220 --> 00:21:15,640
now,

561
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:18,040
what about the eigenvectors of momentum?

562
00:21:18,660 --> 00:21:20,980
The eigenvectors of position

563
00:21:20,980 --> 00:21:22,720
are Dirac delta functions.

564
00:21:23,160 --> 00:21:26,320
They are functions which are zero everywheres

565
00:21:28,879 --> 00:21:34,000
except at the eigenvalue position.

566
00:21:35,860 --> 00:21:37,320
In other words,

567
00:21:37,800 --> 00:21:40,420
the eigenvector representing a particle

568
00:21:40,420 --> 00:21:41,980
known to be at x-north

569
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:44,500
is a function which is zero everywheres

570
00:21:44,500 --> 00:21:45,640
except at x-north,

571
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:47,880
where it's very high and very narrow.

572
00:21:48,680 --> 00:21:51,540
Let's not worry about its precise mathematical definition.

573
00:21:51,700 --> 00:21:53,460
It's called a Dirac delta function.

574
00:21:55,820 --> 00:21:58,260
And it's not too hard to believe

575
00:21:58,260 --> 00:22:00,480
that if the wave function of a particle

576
00:22:00,480 --> 00:22:02,960
is so concentrated at a particular point,

577
00:22:03,160 --> 00:22:05,260
that the probability for finding it

578
00:22:05,260 --> 00:22:07,520
is zero everywheres except at that point.

579
00:22:07,640 --> 00:22:07,800
That,

580
00:22:07,800 --> 00:22:08,100
of course,

581
00:22:08,100 --> 00:22:08,540
makes sense.

582
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:10,040
Now,

583
00:22:10,040 --> 00:22:11,540
what are the states?

584
00:22:11,540 --> 00:22:14,060
The states for which the momentum is certain.

585
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:15,160
In other words,

586
00:22:15,220 --> 00:22:18,300
